Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the U.S. government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had continued to balloon in the face of falling house prices.
Now that the government fully backs Fannie and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial means of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Do not the venerable principles of capitalism include that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to suffer the consequences of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Especially unclear is whether the bailout will actually cost U.S. taxpayers anything in the long run. It may prevent further systemic effects that would cripple the financial sector and thus the world economy.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
In addition, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as having an implicit guarantee from the U.S. government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue action by the U.S. government could undermine confidence in government securities and, because they are associated with these, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the U.S. economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative highs and crashes in asset values, which bring questions of trust, but also of fairness, into the equation.
Similar housing sector highs are now coming to an end in many other countries, and they may be facing the same sufferings – and the same moral dilemmas – that the U.S. economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not only the housing markets.
The stock markets are as well.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose 5 times between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose 5 times in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar highs and crashes in stock markets have occurred in many other countries as well.
As long as they continued, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating in these economies.
Now that they have reversed, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts may be necessary – not to prop up the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when help fails to arrive in the face of collapsing markets.
People's reactions to these events depend on their feelings and their sense of justice.
The described booms and crashes have caused a major redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested in the stock market or the housing market did well or poorly depending on their timing.
People will judge the fairness of these outcomes based on what they were told and what implicit promises they derived from that.
What were people in all these countries told about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find this out.
Policy can only react generally and cannot treat each case individually.
We know that economic growth in recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were capital investments in their markets sold too dearly?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that the boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not starving.
Yet we cannot carelessly conclude from this that all their losses should be left untouched without restriction.
The gnawing problem is one of "honesty and trustworthiness".
National economies flourish only when "honesty and trustworthiness" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative highs have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who have promoted certain capital investments have done so contrary to honesty and trustworthiness.
Take the investors who bought bonds from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to bail them out in a crisis, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
Government officials never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is beginning to discover capitalism and its power to transform economies.
Yet capitalism relies on honesty and trust.
An outcome perceived as unfair can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose trust in companies and are therefore less willing to provide them with their precious capital and labor.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
